post_text:
Transfer Window Now Open for Our Virtual School: Carlsbad Seaside Academy

Carlsbad Seaside Academy (CSA) is the virtual independent study program for students in all grade levels in Carlsbad Unified School District. Our virtual program at CSA will provide the opportunity for students to work closely with a cooperating teacher who will provide a challenging yet nurturing distance learning curriculum.

We’ll be hosting an informational webinar on July 7, 2020 at 6:00 PM. To RSVP and to receive the link to attend the webinar: http://bit.ly/July7RSVP. We’ll record and post it to the website later for those who are unable to attend.

Here's more information: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1AwqSeIaqU85RcIomg2FftVEUoun4eWHO/view?usp=sharing

post_text: We love our teachers! Congrats to our Teacher of the Year, Mrs. Bannock! #cusdlearns
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
2021 Teachers of the Year - YouTube

San Diego County Office of Education
May 4 at 8:05 AM ·

How do you celebrate #TeacherAppreciationWeek during a pandemic? Virtually, of course! Today and every day this week, we will highlight the 2020-21 teachers of the year from San Diego County school districts. These amazing educators stay positive and humble in order to better serve students, and even in a distance-learning format, make their students feel welcome, safe, and loved. Visit our YouTube playlist to meet Arah Allard (Del Mar Hills Elementary, Del Mar Union School District), Hilary Anelli (Lemon Grove Academy Elementary, Lemon Grove School District), Andrea Arroyo (Eastlake Middle School, Sweetwater Union High School District), Kim Arvidson (Empressa Elementary, Vista Unified), Jennifer Bannock (Hope Elementary, Carlsbad Unified School District), Susana Baum (Solana Beach School District), Jessica Borah (Rancho Minerva MS Bulls - VUSD, Vista Unified), Jennifer Cerda (Oceanside Unified School District), and Ellen Cody (Silver Strand Elementary School, Coronado Unified School District). https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLl574UpZ180JI8bKehZOZTipdDagfRVH4

Thank you all for your patience and support as we officially rolled out Remote Online Learning this week. We crunched some numbers early in the week, and we had over 10,300 students access instruction through Google Classroom and Google Meet over the first few days; nearly 94% of our students were online and active this week. I’m very impressed with our students and teachers!

Please note that Spring Break is next week (April 6 through 10). Just like a traditional Spring Break, there will be no teacher-led instruction during this time. Remote Online Learning will begin again on Monday, April 13, and will continue for as long as our school facilities are closed.

Clarification about School Closures in California - April 1, 2020

Today, Governor Gavin Newsom commented in his daily press conference that all school facilities in the state of California should be closed for the rest of the school year, and all districts should fully commit to distance learning for the remainder of the school year.

He did not, however, issue an Executive Order closing all schools for the year.

As such, we are in the same situation as we were yesterday:
1. Our school facilities are closed for the moment;
2. Our teachers will continue to engage students in Remote Online Learning for as long as we’re closed; and
3. We are waiting to hear from the San Diego County public health officer about when we can safely reopen.

Read the full statement here:
https://drive.google.com/open?id=1N8JWER6rAJSGswHbZ1_OGs9yOBX3-AFr

shared_text:
San Diego County Office of Education
March 28 at 7:16 AM ·

The mental health effects of COVID-19 are as important to address as the physical health effects. This is especially true for the one in five who already have mental health conditions – or the one in two who are at risk of developing them.

Be sure to take time this weekend to take care of yourself - take a break from the news, get some fresh air, talk to a friend - so you can help your child through this time. Here are some ways you can create a safe emotional and physical environment for your student.

Find more resources at https://covid-19.sdcoe.net/Parent-Resources.

#StayHome #InItTogether #COVID19 #ParentResources #MentalHealthMatters

shared_text:
City of Carlsbad - Official
March 21 at 8:09 PM ·

Sorry to say that the latest numbers are out, and Carlsbad now has 11 confirmed COVID-19 cases. Starting tomorrow we are closing:

Athletic fields
Basketball courts
Dog parks
Pickleball courts
Picnic amenities
Playgrounds
Skate parks
Tennis courts

Please continue to go outside for walks, but do not gather and do not get closer than 6 feet from each other. We need to all work together on this. Our Police Department can't be at all the parks all the time. We need your help. It's only been 2 days -- some people might not know -- or maybe they don't understand the importance. Be kind to each other and help share this important information.

post_text:
Just a quick reminder about social distancing and California's stay-at-home order - at this time, it’s really important to reduce the possible transmission of COVID-19 by following a few basic principles.

Do the five!
1. HANDS - Wash them often
2. ELBOW - Cough into it
3. FACE - Don’t touch it
4. SPACE - Keep a safe distance (at least six feet apart)
5. HOME - Stay if you can

What is social distancing? Here’s a quick video explanation by Dr. Anthony Fauci, Dr. Deborah Birx, and U.S. Surgeon General Jerome Adams: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nlyxz2X97Do

We’d all like to get back to school and work as quickly as possible; please help reduce the spread of COVID-19 by staying away from groups and gatherings during this critical time.
text:
Just a quick reminder about social distancing and California's stay-at-home order - at this time, it’s really important to reduce the possible transmission of COVID-19 by following a few basic principles.

Do the five!
1. HANDS - Wash them often
2. ELBOW - Cough into it
3. FACE - Don’t touch it
4. SPACE - Keep a safe distance (at least six feet apart)
5. HOME - Stay if you can

What is social distancing? Here’s a quick video explanation by Dr. Anthony Fauci, Dr. Deborah Birx, and U.S. Surgeon General Jerome Adams: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nlyxz2X97Do

We’d all like to get back to school and work as quickly as possible; please help reduce the spread of COVID-19 by staying away from groups and gatherings during this critical time.

post_text:
Update: March 19, 2020

Yesterday we shared with you our newly released Extended Learning Activities website with daily activities for students in grades K through 12. We also shared recommended daily schedules for students to follow while they’re learning at home. Our website currently provides extended learning activities for each day until Spring Break (which begins on April 6).

We’ve received a few questions about why the student activities are not required. Put simply, we currently want to ensure student physical and emotional wellness before requiring completion of learning activities. Many of our students may not be in a place to focus fully on learning right now, and we don’t want to add additional pressure at this time to an already stressful situation.

That said, we're currently working to develop additional tools and resources for online learning; more info to come!

Here's the full message from today with additional info: https://drive.google.com/open?id=1q_KSQ7KAV_SsYnegyPpb4eRtMw5B84Qz

post_text:
Dear Carlsbad Unified families,

We’d like your input! Here are links to our survey, in English and Spanish, for the purposes of engaging teachers, staff, parents, students, and the community in the process of setting next year's goals and priorities.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/STLD97D English

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/NHZR5CM Spanish

These goals and priorities become part of our LCAP (Local Control Accountability Plan), a three-year plan that describes our overall vision for students, the results we expect to achieve, and key actions we will take to achieve these results. The three-year plan will also describe how our District's budget is aligned with our goals and priorities.

This survey will take about 5 minutes to complete. Again, thank you for your time and your support for the education of our students.

Sincerely,

Veronica Williams, President, Board of Trustees
Dr. Ben Churchill, Superintendent

post_text: Thank you to the City of Carlsbad for convening a meeting of superintendents and board members from the four public school districts with schools in Carlsbad. Superintendent Churchill, Board President Williams, and Trustee Pearson met with Mayor Hall, Councilmember Bhat-Patel, and representatives from San Marcos Unified School District, San Dieguito Union High School District, and Encinitas Union School District to discuss collaboration in our schools. Of the approx. 16,000 school aged children in Carlsbad, nearly 12,000 attend Carlsbad Unified schools - we’re proud to work collaboratively with our education partners to support all students, and thankful to have such strong support from the City of Carlsbad. #bettertogether #teamcarlsbad #cusdlearns

post_text: Spotlight on: Magnolia Elementary School! (We’re highlighting one of our sites every school day in December.) Magnolia currently has 46 certificated and classified staff members serving 521 students. Founded in 1957 (making it the oldest campus in our district), Magnolia is scheduled for a full campuswide renovation beginning in June 2020. This modernization will be funded by our Measure MM facilities bond, approved by the voters in Carlsbad in 2018. A unique aspect at Magnolia is their Innovation Lab, funded in large part by donations from the Carlsbad Educational Foundation, which has served as an incubator and design inspiration for our planned deployment of STEAM Labs (for science, technology, engineering, the arts, and mathematics) on all elementary school campuses over the next five years. The Magnolia mascot is the lion. (Photo credit: @maginnovationlab) @magprincipal @carlsbadusd #cusdlearns

post_text: Spotlight on: Pacific Rim Elementary School! (We’re highlighting one of our sites every school day in December.) Founded in 1999, Pacific Rim currently has 53 certificated and classified staff members serving 778 students, making it the largest elementary school in our district. The recipient of many awards, most recently Pac Rim was recognized with the California Distinguished Schools Award and the National Blue Ribbon Schools Award in 2017. The boys’ and girls’ soccer teams at Pac Rim took home the first place trophies in our annual Copa de Carlsbad soccer tournament held at Pine Park last month. Their mascot is the waverider. @pacrimwaveriders @carlsbadusd #cusdlearns

post_text: Spotlight on: Poinsettia Elementary School! (We’re highlighting one of our sites every school day in December.) The school was founded in 2007, making it the most recently constructed elementary school in our district. Their mascot is the panther. Poinsettia currently has 44 certificated and classified staff members serving 458 students. Poinsettia was one of the first schools in Carlsbad to implement Sanford Harmony, a social emotional learning program (developed locally by National University) designed to foster communication, connection, and community both in and outside the classroom. Social emotional learning (SEL) is the process through which children and adults acquire and effectively apply the knowledge, attitudes, and skills necessary for being a healthy adult. This includes problem-solving skills, as well as teaching kids to embrace diversity and build healthy relationships that will last well into adulthood. @poinsettia_elementary @carlsbadusd #cusdlearns

post_text: Spotlight on: Sage Creek High School! (We’re highlighting one of our sites every school day in December.) Founded in 2013, Sage Creek High School currently has 103 certificated and classified staff members serving 1,316 students. The SCHS team works to create an interconnected learning community that prepares students to thrive as responsible citizens in an ever-changing world. Sage Creek has been recognized by the California School Boards Association with a Golden Bell Award, and has been named to the list of best high schools by US News & World Report. Students at Sage Creek are offered a comprehensive a-g curriculum, and can choose from unique College and Career Pathways like Biomedical Science, Engineering, and Computer Science. Recently the Girls’ Cross Country Team won the state championship for the second year in a row. The Sage Creek mascot is the bobcat. @SCbobcats @carlsbadusd #cusdlearns (Photo credit: @anderssonchem)

post_text: Each year we share an infographic at the beginning of the school year with a snapshot of key information. We’re proud that our enrollment has increased again this year, as it has in each of the last several years. We’re proud of our professional and effective staff, and we remain the fourth largest employer in Carlsbad. Our high graduation rate and UC/CSU eligibility rank us among the best districts in California. Our 3rd grade literacy rate - a key predictor of success in high school and beyond - is 30 percentage points higher than the statewide average of 48%. And we do this with the lowest per-student revenue of any unified district in San Diego County. We’re proud of our students, our staff, and our community for helping us provide every student an extraordinary education in an inspiring environment. #cusdlearns

Message from Carlsbad High School:
A short time ago during lunch we were advised by the Carlsbad Police Department (CPD) that there was police activity involving a potentially dangerous suspect in the area around Carlsbad High School. As a precautionary measure we secured the school campus with all students on campus going early into their 6th period classes and redirected students returning to campus from lunch. Within several minutes, the CPD notified us that the suspect was in custody and that the situation was clear. Students and staff did an outstanding job of responding quickly and safely to the incident and we appreciate their efforts.
